            <div type="edition">
            <ab>Thespion</ab></div>
            
            <div type="translation">
            <p>Of the Thespians</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
            <p>"Thespion" may also be translated "of the divinely inspired ones," although all other
                    uses of "Thespion" in the genitive plural refer to the people of Thespiae
                    (Anderson-Zhu 2023).</p>
                <p>This kylix has been identified on stylistic grounds as part of the Sam Wide
                    Group, a collection of ceramic vessels created by a workshop in Corinth in the
                    5th century BCE. All known examples of the group are small vessels likely used
                    for votive purposes. They primarily have decoration of a single figure on the
                    interior, often of divine or comedic figures and some painted decoration on the
                    exterior. No other extant Sam Wide Group vessels have an inscription.</p></div>
            

